value.value: The row of setae that extends along the carina paramandibular process and curves behind the mandibular base.
The carina that extends laterally on the abdominal tergite.
The impression extends along the lateral margin of the metasomal mediotergite.

Basal-most portion of the forewing vein complex that occurs behind the costal cell; measured from the constriction that delimits the humeral plate to the point at which the vein touches the leading edge of the wing apically.
The carina that arises from the anterior mandibular articulation that is located medially of the orbital carina and laterally of the frontal carina.
The carina that is located along the ventral metapleural margin, between the mesocoxal foramen and metacoxal foramen.
The signum that is located submedially on the ventral face of the mesopleuron. The subpleural signum corresponds to the site of origin of the first mesopleuro-mesonotal (pl2-t2a) muscle.
The area that is located ventrally on the pectus.
The groove that corresponds to a ridge.
The area that is located laterally of the longitudinal metanotal carina.
The sclerite that is located dorsally of the anal opening.
The area that is located medially on the lower face between the dorsal margin of the clypeus and the anatomical line that connects the dorsalmost points of the left and right antennal rims.
The line that marks the fusion of two ancestral sclerites.
The setiferous patch that is located on the synsternum.
The translucent patch that is located on the synsternite.
The sternite that is at least two times as long as an adjacent sternite.
The translucent patch that is located submedially on the syntergum.
The sclerite that is composed of fused abdominal terga.
The anatomical structure that is a distinctly delimited group of segments.
The spur that is curved and projects from the apex of the last tarsal segment on either side of the arolium of the pretarsus.
The projection that is median, membraneous and is located distally on the ventral margin of the tarsomere.
The annulus that is the part of the tarsus.
The leg segment that is apical to the tibia.
The cuticular evagination that is located laterally of the preaxilla and obscures the anterior mesonoto-first axillary articulation and the mesopleuro-second axillary sclerite joints.
The tarsomere that is apical.
The area that is located on the gena, posterior to the compound eye.
The cuticular invagination on which a muscle is attached.
The apodeme that extends between the posterior tentorial pit and the anterior tentorial pit.
The apodeme that connects medially the tentorial arms.
The pit on the cranium that corresponds to the tentorium.
The muscle that arises from the dorsal surface of the anterior broadened part of the anterior tentorial arm and inserts on the scape.
The labial muscle that arises from the cranium and inserts on the labium.
The maxillar muscle that arises on the posteroventral part of the anterior tentorial arm and inserts on the median wall of the stipes.
The apodeme that has its sites of origin marked by the anterior and posterior tentorial pits and gular sulci.
The anatomical cluster that is composed of the first and second valvulae.
The sclerite that is located on the tergum.
The area that is located on the integument and is dorsal of the ventral diaphragm.
The gonad that is consisting of testis follicles, is connected with the vas deferens and seminal vesicle.
The tergite that is located in the third abdominal segment.
The axillary sclerite that corresponds to the site of insertion of the mesopleuro-third axillary sclerite muscles and is connected proximally with the fourth axillary sclerite.
The mesonotal muscle that originates from the ventral apodeme of the first phragma and inserts on the acropleural apodeme of the mesopleuron.
The second abdominal tergal muscle that arises from the metaphragma and inserts on the dorsal surface of the second abdominal tergum.
The area of the second valvifer-third valvula complex that is posterior to the distal vertical conjunctiva of the second valvifer-third valvula complex.
The body segment that is located in the thorax.
The sternum that is located on a thoracic segment.
The tagma that is composed of the prothorax, mesothorax and metathorax.
The patch that is located on the gastrocoelus and has specialized sculpture.
The leg segment that is proximal to the tarsus and distal to the femur.
The spur that is located distally on a tibia.
The projection that is located distally on the mandible.
